00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:05.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington D.C.

00:00:22.630 --> 00:00:24.880
&gt;&gt; Anya Creightney: Well thanks
again for joining us today

00:00:24.880 --> 00:00:28.890
to celebrate the birthday of a very
special writer, Flannery O'Connor.

00:00:28.890 --> 00:00:33.010 position:56%
My name is Anya Creightney and I am
the program specialist of the Poetry

00:00:33.010 --> 00:00:36.260
and Literature Center at
the Library of Congress.

00:00:36.260 --> 00:00:39.530
I am also a proud partner
in this series, representing

00:00:39.530 --> 00:00:41.710
and celebrating the careers of many

00:00:41.710 --> 00:00:44.930
of our most valuable
literary voices.

00:00:44.930 --> 00:00:47.560
I'm especially happy
today as this event,

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:50.690
Flannery O'Connor's literary
birthday celebration,

00:00:50.690 --> 00:00:53.330
has been two years in the making.

00:00:53.330 --> 00:00:56.630
The event was originally
slated for last year and due

00:00:56.630 --> 00:01:00.880
to scheduling conflicts we
initially abandoned our concept

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:02.500
of celebrating Flannery.

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:06.240
But ultimately genuine
curiosity and admiration

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:09.300
of O'Connor kept Flannery
in our minds.

00:01:09.300 --> 00:01:12.550
So it's with unique, so it
is with this unique pleasure

00:01:12.550 --> 00:01:15.060
that I welcome our
participants Emily Mitchell

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:17.940
and Bonnie Jo Campbell here today.

00:01:17.940 --> 00:01:22.290 position:56%
Before sharing a little bit about
the organization of today's program,

00:01:22.290 --> 00:01:25.940
I just want to tell you a
little bit about our authors.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:28.430
Bonnie Jo Campbell is
the author of two novels.

00:01:28.430 --> 00:01:33.370
Once Upon a River, a national
best seller, and Q Road.

00:01:33.370 --> 00:01:36.890 position:56%
Her critically acclaimed short
fiction collections include American

00:01:36.890 --> 00:01:41.060
Salvage, Women and Other
Animals, and most recently,

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:45.580
Mothers Tell Your Daughters,
published in the fall of 2015

00:01:45.580 --> 00:01:48.760
and also on sale in the back.

00:01:48.760 --> 00:01:52.190
Emily Mitchell's debut novel,
the Last Summer of the World,

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:56.050
was published by Norton
in 2007 and was a finalist

00:01:56.050 --> 00:02:00.330
for the New York Public
Library Young Lions Award.

00:02:00.330 --> 00:02:03.090
Her first collection of
short stories, Viral,

00:02:03.090 --> 00:02:07.840
was published in June 2015 and was
described by the New York Book,

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:12.980
excuse me, New York Times
Book Review as quote alluring,

00:02:12.980 --> 00:02:17.620
the best stories here pushed
towards true heartbreak, end quote.

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:21.490
Emily teaches locally at
the University of Maryland.

00:02:21.490 --> 00:02:24.060
And now, just for a
little event breakdown

00:02:24.060 --> 00:02:26.000
so that you're all with us.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:28.990
Each writer will lecture
for approximately 20 minutes

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:32.760
and both will conclude by
sharing excerpts of her work.

00:02:32.760 --> 00:02:35.270
Afterward we will break
slightly with tradition

00:02:35.270 --> 00:02:38.680
and both authors will take
questions from the audience

00:02:38.680 --> 00:02:40.550
after their reading, so be thinking

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:44.580
or notating your questions
during their lecture.

00:02:44.580 --> 00:02:48.230
And lastly before I turn it over,
I just want to remind everyone

00:02:48.230 --> 00:02:51.530
to turn off their cell phones
or anything that would interrupt

00:02:51.530 --> 00:02:53.790
with today's programming.

00:02:53.790 --> 00:02:57.850
And let me also remind you that the
Poetry and Literature Center puts

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:02.270
on 30 to 40 public programs
just like this one every year.

00:03:02.270 --> 00:03:04.110
So, if you're interested
to find more

00:03:04.110 --> 00:03:08.320
out about this particular series
or others, please put your name

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:10.900
on our email list in
the back of the room.

00:03:10.900 --> 00:03:15.610
And without further ado, you guys
will help me welcome our writers.

00:03:15.610 --> 00:03:19.290
And first up is Emily Mitchell,
followed by Bonnie Jo Campbell.

00:03:19.290 --> 00:03:21.090
Thank you.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:25.500
[ Applause ]

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:31.720
&gt;&gt; Emily Mitchell:
Gosh, thank you to Anya

00:03:31.720 --> 00:03:33.490
for that lovely introduction.

00:03:33.490 --> 00:03:39.710
I am so pleased and a little
daunted to be here today.

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:45.490
In Flannery O'Connor's story, A
Late Encounter with the Enemy,

00:03:45.490 --> 00:03:49.760
the reader meets General
Tennessee Flintrock Sash,

00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:53.540
a 104-year-old Confederate veteran.

00:03:53.540 --> 00:03:56.150
And the 64-year-old granddaughter

00:03:56.150 --> 00:04:00.000
with whom he lives,
Sally Poker Sash.

00:04:02.150 --> 00:04:04.110
Thank you.

00:04:04.110 --> 00:04:07.110
General Sash we learn
was in fact not a general

00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:09.710
in the Civil War or
in any other war.

00:04:09.710 --> 00:04:15.400 position:56%
He acquired his much admired uniform
as part of the promotional pageantry

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:18.590
from a movie premiere
just 12 years earlier.

00:04:18.590 --> 00:04:22.330
Now, in the narrative
present of the story,

00:04:22.330 --> 00:04:27.710
the wheelchair bound general is
attending Sally Poker's belated

00:04:27.710 --> 00:04:30.460
graduation from teaching college.

00:04:30.460 --> 00:04:35.660
He has been left in the care of
a young boy called John Wesley

00:04:35.660 --> 00:04:40.910
who has been tasked to bring him
up onto the stage for the ceremony.

00:04:42.550 --> 00:04:47.420
The graduates in their heavy
robes, looked as if the last beads

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:51.440
of ignorance were being
sweated out of them.

00:04:51.440 --> 00:04:55.280
The sun blazed off the
fenders of automobiles and beat

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:57.660
from the columns of
buildings and pulled the eye

00:04:57.660 --> 00:05:00.540
from one spot of glare to another.

00:05:00.540 --> 00:05:04.620
It pulled Sally Poker's toward
the big red Coca Cola machine

00:05:04.620 --> 00:05:08.000
that had been set up by
the side of the auditorium.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:12.850
Here she saw the General parked,
scowling and hatless in his chair

00:05:12.850 --> 00:05:14.910
in the blazing sun,
while John Wesley,

00:05:14.910 --> 00:05:18.350
his blouse loose behind
his hip and cheek pressed

00:05:18.350 --> 00:05:21.810
to the red machine was
drinking a Coca Cola.

00:05:21.810 --> 00:05:25.330 position:56%
She broke from the line and galloped
to him and snatched the bottle away.

00:05:25.330 --> 00:05:28.340
She shook the boy and
thrust in his blouse

00:05:28.340 --> 00:05:31.050
and put the hat on
the old man's head.

00:05:31.050 --> 00:05:34.390
Now get him in there, she
said, pointing one rigid finger

00:05:34.390 --> 00:05:37.030
to the side door of the building.

00:05:37.030 --> 00:05:42.490 position:56%
For his part, the General felt as if
there were a little hole beginning

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:46.830
to develop and widen
in the top of his head.

00:05:46.830 --> 00:05:51.220
The boy wheeled rapidly down a walk
and up a ramp and into a building

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:53.170
and bumped him over
the stage entrance

00:05:53.170 --> 00:05:56.170
and into position where
he had been told.

00:05:56.170 --> 00:05:59.900
And the General glared in front
of him at heads that all seemed

00:05:59.900 --> 00:06:04.380
that to flow together and eyes that
moved from one face to another.

00:06:04.380 --> 00:06:09.440 position:56%
Several figures in black robes came
and picked up his hand and shook it.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:13.790
A black procession was following
up each aisle and forming

00:06:13.790 --> 00:06:17.660
to stately music in a
pool in front of him.

00:06:17.660 --> 00:06:21.050
The music seemed to be entering
his head through the little hole

00:06:21.050 --> 00:06:24.440
and he thought for a second
that the procession would try

00:06:24.440 --> 00:06:26.460
to enter it too.

00:06:26.460 --> 00:06:28.940
He didn't know what
procession this was,

00:06:28.940 --> 00:06:31.100
but there was something
familiar about it.

00:06:31.100 --> 00:06:34.700
It must be familiar to him since it
had come to meet him and he didn't

00:06:34.700 --> 00:06:36.470
like the black procession.

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:40.250
And any procession that came to
meet him, he thought irritably,

00:06:40.250 --> 00:06:42.730
ought to have floats with
beautiful girls on them.

00:06:42.730 --> 00:06:45.120
Like the floats before the premier.

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:47.740
It must be something
connected with history

00:06:47.740 --> 00:06:49.900
like they were always having.

00:06:49.900 --> 00:06:52.050
He had no use for any of it.

00:06:52.050 --> 00:06:53.870
What happened then wasn't anything

00:06:53.870 --> 00:06:57.570
to a man living now
and he was living now.

00:06:57.570 --> 00:07:00.870
When all the procession had
flowed into the black pool,

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:03.420
a black figure began
orating in front of it.

00:07:03.420 --> 00:07:07.060
The figure was telling something
about history and the General made

00:07:07.060 --> 00:07:09.170
up his mind he wouldn't listen.

00:07:09.170 --> 00:07:12.420
But the words kept seeping through
the little hole in his head.

00:07:12.420 --> 00:07:15.170
He heard his own name mentioned

00:07:15.170 --> 00:07:17.630
and his chair was shuffled
forward roughly,

00:07:17.630 --> 00:07:19.740
and the boy scout took a big bow.

00:07:19.740 --> 00:07:22.270
They called his name
and the fat brat bowed.

00:07:22.270 --> 00:07:24.350
God damn you, the old
man tried to say,

00:07:24.350 --> 00:07:26.770
get out of my way, I can stand up.

00:07:26.770 --> 00:07:29.350
But he was jerked back again
and before he could get up

00:07:29.350 --> 00:07:33.480
and take his bow, he supposed
the noise they made was for him.

00:07:33.480 --> 00:07:36.560
If he was over he didn't intend
to listen to any more of it.

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:39.940
If it hadn't been for the little
hole in the top of his head,

00:07:39.940 --> 00:07:42.570
none of the words would
have gotten to him.

00:07:42.570 --> 00:07:45.880
He thought of putting a finger up
there into the hole to block them,

00:07:45.880 --> 00:07:49.330
but the hole was a little wider
than his finger and it felt

00:07:49.330 --> 00:07:51.580
as if it was getting deeper.

00:07:51.580 --> 00:07:54.480
Another black robe had taken
the place of the first one

00:07:54.480 --> 00:07:58.610
and was talking now and he
heard his name mentioned again,

00:07:58.610 --> 00:08:02.390 position:56%
but they were not talking about him,
but they were talking about history.

00:08:02.390 --> 00:08:05.130
If we forget our past,
the speaker was saying,

00:08:05.130 --> 00:08:07.780
we won't remember our
future and it will be

00:08:07.780 --> 00:08:10.570
as well for we won't have one.

00:08:10.570 --> 00:08:13.980
The General heard some
of these words gradually.

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:17.910
He had forgotten history and he
didn't intend to remember it again.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:21.720
He had forgotten the name and
face of his wife and the names

00:08:21.720 --> 00:08:23.670
and faces of his children.

00:08:23.670 --> 00:08:25.920
Or even if he had a
wife and children.

00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:30.550
And he had forgotten the name and
places and the places themselves.

00:08:30.550 --> 00:08:32.850
And what had happened at them.

00:08:32.850 --> 00:08:35.840
He was considerably irked
by the hole in his head.

00:08:35.840 --> 00:08:40.550
He had not expected to have a
hole in his head at this event.

00:08:40.550 --> 00:08:44.600
It was the slow black music
that had put it there.

00:08:44.600 --> 00:08:47.830
And though most of the
music had stopped outside,

00:08:47.830 --> 00:08:52.320
there was still a little of it in
the hole going deeper and moving

00:08:52.320 --> 00:08:54.640
around in his thoughts,
letting the words he heard

00:08:54.640 --> 00:08:57.150
into the dark places of his brain.

00:08:57.150 --> 00:08:59.830 position:56%
He had heard the words, Chickamauga.

00:08:59.830 --> 00:09:01.430
Shiloh, Johnston, and Lee.

00:09:01.430 --> 00:09:04.520
And he knew he was
inspiring all these words

00:09:04.520 --> 00:09:06.180
that meant nothing to him.

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:10.250
He wondered if he had been a
General at Chickamauga or at Lee.

00:09:10.250 --> 00:09:13.700
Then he tried to see himself and
the horse mounted in the middle

00:09:13.700 --> 00:09:16.900
of the float full of beautiful
girls being driven slowly

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:19.030
through downtown Atlanta.

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:24.060 position:56%
Instead, the old words began to stir
in his head as if they were trying

00:09:24.060 --> 00:09:28.110
to wrench themselves out
of place and come to life.

00:09:28.110 --> 00:09:33.630 position:56%
The speaker was through with that
war and had gone on to the next one.

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:35.470 position:56%
And now, he was approaching another.

00:09:35.470 --> 00:09:39.480 position:56%
And all of his words, like the black
procession were vaguely familiar

00:09:39.480 --> 00:09:41.110
and irritating.

00:09:41.110 --> 00:09:43.090
There was a long finger of music

00:09:43.090 --> 00:09:46.010
in the General's head
probing various spots

00:09:46.010 --> 00:09:48.980
that were words letting in
a little light on the words

00:09:48.980 --> 00:09:50.890
and helping them to live.

00:09:50.890 --> 00:09:53.220
The words that, the words began

00:09:53.220 --> 00:09:55.570
to come towards him
and he said, Damn it.

00:09:55.570 --> 00:09:57.350
I ain't going to have it.

00:09:57.350 --> 00:10:00.140
And he started edging
backwards to get out of the way.

00:10:00.140 --> 00:10:04.020
Then he saw the figure in the black
robe sit down and there was a noise

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:07.110
and the black pool in front
of him began to rumble

00:10:07.110 --> 00:10:11.590
and to flow towards him from either
side, like the black slow music.

00:10:11.590 --> 00:10:12.890
And he said, Stop, damn it.

00:10:12.890 --> 00:10:15.450
I can't do but one thing at a time.

00:10:15.450 --> 00:10:17.310
He couldn't protect
himself from the words

00:10:17.310 --> 00:10:19.180
and attend to the procession too.

00:10:19.180 --> 00:10:21.700
And the words were
coming at him fast.

00:10:21.700 --> 00:10:23.810
He felt that he was
running backwards

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:26.890
and the words were coming
at him like musket fire.

00:10:26.890 --> 00:10:31.030
Just escaping him, but
getting nearer and nearer.

00:10:31.030 --> 00:10:34.510
He turned around and began
to run as fast as he could,

00:10:34.510 --> 00:10:36.890
but he found himself
running towards the words.

00:10:36.890 --> 00:10:39.460
He was running into a
regular volley of them

00:10:39.460 --> 00:10:41.750
and meeting them with quick curses.

00:10:41.750 --> 00:10:47.920
As the music swirled towards him
the entire past opened up on him

00:10:47.920 --> 00:10:51.560
out of nowhere, and he felt his
body riddled in a 100 places

00:10:51.560 --> 00:10:53.450
with the sharp stabs of pain.

00:10:53.450 --> 00:10:57.380
And he fell down, returning
a curse for every hit.

00:10:57.380 --> 00:11:00.550
He saw his wife's narrow face
looking at him critically

00:11:00.550 --> 00:11:03.040
through her round gold
framed glasses.

00:11:03.040 --> 00:11:06.860
He saw one of his squinting
bald headed sons

00:11:06.860 --> 00:11:09.690
and his mother run towards
him with an anxious look.

00:11:09.690 --> 00:11:14.490
And a succession of places,
Chickamauga, Shiloh, Marthasville,

00:11:14.490 --> 00:11:18.040
rush at him as if the past
was the only future now

00:11:18.040 --> 00:11:19.400
and he had to endure it.

00:11:19.400 --> 00:11:24.250
Then suddenly he saw that the
black procession was almost on him.

00:11:24.250 --> 00:11:25.860
He recognized it.

00:11:25.860 --> 00:11:28.400
For it had been dogging
him all his days.

00:11:28.400 --> 00:11:31.870
He made a desperate effort
to see over it and find

00:11:31.870 --> 00:11:35.370
out what comes after
the past and that.

00:11:35.370 --> 00:11:39.390 position:56%
He made a such a desperate effort to
see over it and find out what comes

00:11:39.390 --> 00:11:42.220
after the past, that his
hand clenched the sword

00:11:42.220 --> 00:11:45.470
until the blade touched bone.

00:11:45.470 --> 00:11:48.800
The graduates were crossing
the stage in a lone file

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:52.280
to receive their scrolls and
shake the President's hand.

00:11:52.280 --> 00:11:58.150
As Sally Poker was near the end,
crossed, she glanced at the General

00:11:58.150 --> 00:12:02.380
and saw him sitting fixed and
fierce, his eyes wide open

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:04.650
and she turned her
head forward again

00:12:04.650 --> 00:12:09.440
and held it a perceptible degree
higher and received her scroll.

00:12:09.440 --> 00:12:14.500 position:56%
Once it was over, and she was out of
the auditorium and in the sun again,

00:12:14.500 --> 00:12:18.620
she located her kin and they waited
together on the bench in the shade

00:12:18.620 --> 00:12:21.280
for John Wesley to
wheel the old man out.

00:12:21.280 --> 00:12:25.160
That crafty scout had bumped him
out the back way and rolled him

00:12:25.160 --> 00:12:30.050
at high speed down a flagstone path
and was waiting now with the corpse

00:12:30.050 --> 00:12:33.130
in the long line at
the Coca Cola machine.

00:12:33.130 --> 00:12:40.350
As I said, I am pleased and a
little daunted to be here today.

00:12:40.350 --> 00:12:46.150
I'm by no means an expert on
Flannery O'Connor and I'm certain

00:12:46.150 --> 00:12:50.950 position:56%
that there are people here
listening who know a great deal more

00:12:50.950 --> 00:12:53.510
about her life and works than I do.

00:12:53.510 --> 00:12:56.300
But what I am is somebody
who writes short stories

00:12:56.300 --> 00:12:57.850
and aspires to write them well.

00:12:57.850 --> 00:13:02.280
And in that capacity I want to
talk a little bit about O'Connor

00:13:02.280 --> 00:13:05.440
and what her work means to me.

00:13:05.440 --> 00:13:10.400
The passage I just read exemplifies
some of the aspects of her work

00:13:10.400 --> 00:13:14.430
that I admire the most and
that I found the most valuable

00:13:14.430 --> 00:13:17.790
to my own development as a writer.

00:13:17.790 --> 00:13:20.870
O'Connor is justly known
as a writer who evokes

00:13:20.870 --> 00:13:23.630
with tremendous precision
the conventions and manners

00:13:23.630 --> 00:13:25.600
of her own time and place.

00:13:25.600 --> 00:13:29.830
But she's also I think a
great writer of ghost stories.

00:13:29.830 --> 00:13:33.530
She is a great observer
and chronicler of the ways

00:13:33.530 --> 00:13:39.150
in which human beings and perhaps
American human beings especially

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:40.450
are haunted.

00:13:40.450 --> 00:13:44.870
We are haunted by the past and
we are haunted by those aspects

00:13:44.870 --> 00:13:49.570 position:56%
of the world that we are least happy
to acknowledge and quickest to deny.

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:53.720
And this haunting in
only intensified

00:13:53.720 --> 00:14:03.390
and perhaps is even caused by
our concerted efforts to escape,

00:14:03.390 --> 00:14:10.080
to be reborn and renewed, to
transcend, to overcome by an act

00:14:10.080 --> 00:14:12.250
of personal determination.

00:14:12.250 --> 00:14:15.530
The more we insist
that we have moved on,

00:14:15.530 --> 00:14:21.330
that we are as General Sash puts
it, living now, the more what we,

00:14:21.330 --> 00:14:25.000
what we wish to deny dogs us.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.190
O'Connor characters draw to
themselves the vary things

00:14:28.190 --> 00:14:30.040
that they dread the most.

00:14:30.040 --> 00:14:34.080
The people and events which disrupt
their comfortable assumptions.

00:14:34.080 --> 00:14:35.600
And in O'Connor's view, of course,

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:38.580
such disruption is precisely
what we need in order

00:14:38.580 --> 00:14:41.480
that we might have the
possibility of experiencing grace.

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:46.040
I first came across O'Connor's
stories and essays in college

00:14:46.040 --> 00:14:50.170
and I found in her uncompromising
depictions the permission

00:14:50.170 --> 00:14:53.470
that I needed to pursue
my own fledgling fiction.

00:14:53.470 --> 00:14:55.870
I learned from her that
your characters need not

00:14:55.870 --> 00:14:57.900
to likable to be fascinating.

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:00.560
That the purpose of
a story is to reveal

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:03.440
and not necessarily to resolve.

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:06.040
I learned that the
meaning of a story must be

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:08.930
to use O'Connor's words,
experienced meaning.

00:15:08.930 --> 00:15:12.290
A story she says is a
way to say something

00:15:12.290 --> 00:15:14.860
that can't be said any other way.

00:15:14.860 --> 00:15:17.290
I learned that a story
must grow its own meaning

00:15:17.290 --> 00:15:19.610
over the course of its unfolding.

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:23.570
The characters and the objects
in the story accumulating meaning

00:15:23.570 --> 00:15:25.450 position:56%
from the action of the story itself.

00:15:25.450 --> 00:15:30.190 position:56%
But most importantly, I learned that
the boundary between the present

00:15:30.190 --> 00:15:32.410
and the past is very thin indeed

00:15:32.410 --> 00:15:36.120
and sometimes it disintegrates
altogether.

00:15:36.120 --> 00:15:42.020
So I'm going to finish with a short
story from my first collection

00:15:42.020 --> 00:15:46.280
that I think owes its existence
to O'Connor in this respect.

00:15:46.280 --> 00:15:58.370
It's called, A Boy My
Sister Dated in High School.

00:15:58.370 --> 00:16:01.860
A boy my sister dated in
high school slapped her

00:16:01.860 --> 00:16:05.120
across the face during an argument.

00:16:05.120 --> 00:16:07.700
They were sitting in the
front seat of his car,

00:16:07.700 --> 00:16:10.370
parked by the basketball
court behind our house,

00:16:10.370 --> 00:16:14.140
and she made a sarcastic reply
to something he had said.

00:16:14.140 --> 00:16:17.110
And before she knew what was
happening, he'd raised his hand

00:16:17.110 --> 00:16:20.290
and swung it, open-palmed,
against her cheek.

00:16:20.290 --> 00:16:24.260
She didn't tell me about
this until years later

00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:26.820
after we had both left home.

00:16:26.820 --> 00:16:31.720 position:56%
When she did tell me, I felt at
once angry and then strangely guilty

00:16:31.720 --> 00:16:35.550
because the boy in question was
extraordinarily good-looking

00:16:35.550 --> 00:16:38.790
and I remembered having been
impressed in a shallow way

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:42.200
that I never spoke about that
my sister was dating someone

00:16:42.200 --> 00:16:43.500
so handsome.

00:16:43.500 --> 00:16:47.120
I was jealous of a lot of things
about my sister in those days:

00:16:47.120 --> 00:16:49.510 position:56%
her beauty and her ease with people,

00:16:49.510 --> 00:16:53.470
how spontaneously funny she
could be, how well she was liked.

00:16:53.470 --> 00:16:57.430
She fit in at our school and
in our town, in her own body,

00:16:57.430 --> 00:17:01.430
in a way that I could not seem
to manage, quiet and bookish

00:17:01.430 --> 00:17:04.590
and peculiar as I was
then and remain.

00:17:04.590 --> 00:17:08.390
Still, there was never a time
when I didn't love her very much

00:17:08.390 --> 00:17:10.960
and when I wouldn't have
done whatever I could

00:17:10.960 --> 00:17:13.220
to support and defend her.

00:17:13.220 --> 00:17:15.200
Why didn't you tell me sooner?

00:17:15.200 --> 00:17:18.070
I asked, when she finally told did.

00:17:18.070 --> 00:17:20.520
When the boy she was
dating hit my sister,

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:24.290
it made a sharp cracking sound,
just like it does in the movies.

00:17:24.290 --> 00:17:28.200
She raised her hand and touched
the side of her own face.

00:17:28.200 --> 00:17:30.910
The expanse of skin where
he'd struck her buzzed

00:17:30.910 --> 00:17:33.130
and tingled, felt weirdly alive.

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:37.520
It didn't hurt or, and even
the actual slap itself hadn't

00:17:37.520 --> 00:17:39.640
really hurt.

00:17:39.640 --> 00:17:43.460
Instead, she was shocked, surprised
because she had not expected this,

00:17:43.460 --> 00:17:46.610
and then confused about
what she should do next.

00:17:46.610 --> 00:17:49.970
She looked over at the boy she
was dating, who had just hit her.

00:17:49.970 --> 00:17:55.920
He was leaning way back against,
away from her against the car door

00:17:55.920 --> 00:18:01.010
as if he was afraid, either of
her or of what he had just done.

00:18:01.010 --> 00:18:05.370
In her eyes was an expression of
shock and remorse much more intense

00:18:05.370 --> 00:18:08.510
than anything she herself
seemed to be feeling.

00:18:08.510 --> 00:18:10.390
He too had been surprised,

00:18:10.390 --> 00:18:13.160
and he looked like he
might be about to cry.

00:18:13.160 --> 00:18:16.520
At that moment it came
into her mind that maybe,

00:18:16.520 --> 00:18:20.650
in punishment for what he had done,
the gods had magically frozen him

00:18:20.650 --> 00:18:24.600
in his current physical position:
curled up like a frightened fetus

00:18:24.600 --> 00:18:27.330
with his eyes bugged out and
his mouth hanging slightly open.

00:18:27.330 --> 00:18:31.050
Perhaps he would be
stuck like that forever.

00:18:31.050 --> 00:18:33.520
In her mind she envisioned
having to explain

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:37.130
to the boy's mother how her
son had come to be paralyzed

00:18:37.130 --> 00:18:40.210
in this posture: He hit me,
she would say, and then, well,

00:18:40.210 --> 00:18:42.470
now he doesn't seem
able to move or speak.

00:18:42.470 --> 00:18:43.940
I'm sorry.

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:48.270
She thought of him in various
scenes over the course of his life

00:18:48.270 --> 00:18:53.080 position:56%
to come-in school, at home, in
church-still fixed in that attitude.

00:18:53.080 --> 00:18:55.260
And the absurdity of
these images together

00:18:55.260 --> 00:18:57.090
with the amazement she still felt

00:18:57.090 --> 00:19:01.180
at what had just occurred made
her suddenly snort with laughter.

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:04.560
Her laughter seemed to free
the boy from his paralysis.

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:05.860
"Oh, God," he said.

00:19:05.860 --> 00:19:07.160
"I'm so sorry.

00:19:07.160 --> 00:19:08.460
I'm so, so sorry.

00:19:08.460 --> 00:19:12.050
I didn't mean-" He reached out
towards her as though he wanted

00:19:12.050 --> 00:19:15.240
to take back what he'd done,
but then he withdrew his hand.

00:19:15.240 --> 00:19:16.830
"I'm sorry," he said again.

00:19:16.830 --> 00:19:18.130
He hung his head.

00:19:18.130 --> 00:19:20.890
"I guess you should take
me home," my sister said.

00:19:20.890 --> 00:19:23.460
Suddenly she felt like crying.

00:19:23.460 --> 00:19:25.880
He nodded and started the car.

00:19:25.880 --> 00:19:28.060
When they pulled up in
front of my parents' house,

00:19:28.060 --> 00:19:29.450
he turned off the engine.

00:19:29.450 --> 00:19:31.710
He looked over at her mournfully.

00:19:31.710 --> 00:19:34.240
She suddenly thought that
he was making a huge,

00:19:34.240 --> 00:19:36.170
self-centered melodrama
out of something

00:19:36.170 --> 00:19:38.300
that really wasn't so important.

00:19:38.300 --> 00:19:40.870
He wanted to be a terrible,
unforgivable villain

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:43.510
and she did not want to
give him that satisfaction.

00:19:43.510 --> 00:19:44.810
"Look," she said.

00:19:44.810 --> 00:19:46.110
"I'm okay.

00:19:46.110 --> 00:19:47.410
It doesn't hurt.

00:19:47.410 --> 00:19:48.710
I'm not, like, scarred
for life or anything."

00:19:48.710 --> 00:19:50.010
"Really?" he asked.

00:19:50.010 --> 00:19:51.310
"Really," she said.

00:19:51.310 --> 00:19:54.150
She leaned over and
kissed him on the cheek.

00:19:54.150 --> 00:19:56.700
He clasped her hands gratefully.

00:19:56.700 --> 00:19:58.480
They smiled at each other

00:19:58.480 --> 00:20:01.020
because that was what
they were used to doing.

00:20:01.020 --> 00:20:03.850
When they smiled, it
felt for a moment,

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:07.700
it felt as if a moment before they
had been drowning in some cold,

00:20:07.700 --> 00:20:11.200
unpleasant sea, and now they
were back on solid ground,

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:12.960
back in the world they knew.

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:15.670
A wave of relief swept over them.

00:20:15.670 --> 00:20:18.860
"You were being kind
of a bitch," he said.

00:20:18.860 --> 00:20:20.250
"I was," she conceded.

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:22.930
"And you were being
a class-one a-hole."

00:20:22.930 --> 00:20:24.550
She opened the door and got out.

00:20:24.550 --> 00:20:26.220
"Can I call you tomorrow?"

00:20:26.220 --> 00:20:27.820
he said after her.

00:20:27.820 --> 00:20:30.450
"Yes," she said and went inside.

00:20:30.450 --> 00:20:34.350
She could hardly even feel where
he had hit her at all anymore.

00:20:34.350 --> 00:20:37.950 position:56%
Because they had made up and because
she wasn't hurt, she didn't feel

00:20:37.950 --> 00:20:40.650
like she needed to mention
to anyone what had happened.

00:20:40.650 --> 00:20:43.660
If she said anything to
our mother, she thought,

00:20:43.660 --> 00:20:45.060
she would only overreact.

00:20:45.060 --> 00:20:47.440
She would call the school,
and maybe the boy's parents.

00:20:47.440 --> 00:20:51.090
She would say things about violence
against women and the patriarchy,

00:20:51.090 --> 00:20:54.260
the kind of embarrassing things
that my sister had to do her best

00:20:54.260 --> 00:20:57.000
to ignore so she would
not be an outcast

00:20:57.000 --> 00:20:58.670
in the conservative
suburb where we lived.

00:20:58.670 --> 00:21:02.440
If she told our mother and
she started making a fuss,

00:21:02.440 --> 00:21:03.940
it would definitely mean that she

00:21:03.940 --> 00:21:06.330
and the boy would break
up and stop dating.

00:21:06.330 --> 00:21:08.530
They were both part of
a big group of friends.

00:21:08.530 --> 00:21:10.790
And she did not want to
cause problems in that group

00:21:10.790 --> 00:21:13.930
over something that was
really, truly no big deal

00:21:13.930 --> 00:21:17.120
but that might become a big deal
if the parents were involved.

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:19.430
It wasn't like she was some
battered or abused woman,

00:21:19.430 --> 00:21:21.460
like she saw on television
talk shows

00:21:21.460 --> 00:21:23.000
or heard about on the local news.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:25.080
Probably, in a few months,

00:21:25.080 --> 00:21:28.720
she wouldn't even remember
that it had happened.

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:31.470
So she said nothing and
the boy never did it again

00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:35.050
and after a while they broke
up for unrelated reasons

00:21:35.050 --> 00:21:37.930
and started dating other
people without much drama

00:21:37.930 --> 00:21:40.000
or distress to either of them.

00:21:40.000 --> 00:21:43.620
They finished high school,
went on to different colleges.

00:21:43.620 --> 00:21:45.440
They didn't keep in touch.

00:21:45.440 --> 00:21:48.370
But during that time, unlike
what she had expected,

00:21:48.370 --> 00:21:53.410
the memory of being hit by the boy
didn't just fade away and vanish.

00:21:53.410 --> 00:21:56.020
It wasn't that she thought
about it all the time

00:21:56.020 --> 00:21:57.320
or that it ruined her life

00:21:57.320 --> 00:22:00.430
or that she could never trust a
man again or anything like that.

00:22:00.430 --> 00:22:04.580
But from time to time it would
come into her mind, that day,

00:22:04.580 --> 00:22:07.040
the moment of surprised
confusion afterward.

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:11.100
And she came to feel, especially
as she got a little older,

00:22:11.100 --> 00:22:14.580
that she had let herself down
by the way she had reacted.

00:22:14.580 --> 00:22:18.640
This was the feeling that
grew incrementally inside her.

00:22:18.640 --> 00:22:20.990
She should not have tried
to make him feel better

00:22:20.990 --> 00:22:22.590
by telling him it was no big deal.

00:22:22.590 --> 00:22:26.070
She should not have kept
it from their friends just

00:22:26.070 --> 00:22:28.070
so they could all continue
to get along.

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:31.150
From the beginning she had
failed to stand up for herself,

00:22:31.150 --> 00:22:33.950
and now she knew, or
felt like she knew,

00:22:33.950 --> 00:22:36.230
about herself that she
would let someone do

00:22:36.230 --> 00:22:38.750
that and do nothing about it.

00:22:38.750 --> 00:22:40.520
She would be obliging.

00:22:40.520 --> 00:22:42.780
She would comply.

00:22:42.780 --> 00:22:46.210
This guilt about how she
hadn't stood up for herself was

00:22:46.210 --> 00:22:49.590
like a small stone that
she had to carry around.

00:22:49.590 --> 00:22:50.960
That was how she pictured it.

00:22:50.960 --> 00:22:53.650
Small and round, but heavy.

00:22:53.650 --> 00:22:57.760
And she came to believe, she
said, when she finally told me

00:22:57.760 --> 00:23:00.010
about it all those years later.

00:23:00.010 --> 00:23:03.510
That maybe if she told people
about it, as she was doing now,

00:23:03.510 --> 00:23:05.590
it would get smaller and lighter.

00:23:05.590 --> 00:23:10.370
That sharing would diminish
it, make it, make it smaller,

00:23:10.370 --> 00:23:13.830
make it maybe even vanish.

00:23:13.830 --> 00:23:16.990
And I thought, but
did not say: maybe,

00:23:16.990 --> 00:23:20.240
or maybe it will make it multiply.

00:23:20.240 --> 00:23:22.040
Thank you.

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:32.050
