00:23:50.390 --> 00:23:55.310
about Flannery O'Connor I shouted
into the phone, I'm unworthy.

00:23:55.310 --> 00:23:58.960
And I fanned myself
with a very short story.

00:23:58.960 --> 00:24:03.380
And I'm not an academic, I said,
I'm just a gal who loves stories

00:24:03.380 --> 00:24:07.980
and chickens and the work
of Flannery O'Connor.

00:24:07.980 --> 00:24:10.540
And the truth is when I think
about Flannery O'Connor,

00:24:10.540 --> 00:24:15.500
I think about a barnyard fowl
and I will stand by my claim

00:24:15.500 --> 00:24:18.010
that each chicken is
a unique individual.

00:24:18.010 --> 00:24:22.570
And I'm hoping someday to write a
book about women and their birds.

00:24:22.570 --> 00:24:26.680
And the essay, in the essay
called Flannery's Fowl,

00:24:26.680 --> 00:24:31.930
I will describe how she smuggled
ducklings onto the airplane

00:24:31.930 --> 00:24:34.740
for the children of her
friends, the Fitzgeralds.

00:24:34.740 --> 00:24:40.160
And how as a kid she taught
a chicken to walk backwards.

00:24:40.160 --> 00:24:44.780
It was the high point of her
life she said decades later.

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:51.180
She was wrong that nobody, wrong
in saying that nobody would want

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:53.400
to hear about her life
in the future.

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:57.220
A life lived quote between the
house and the chicken yard,

00:24:57.220 --> 00:25:00.240
which I think is the name of the
biography, the recent biography.

00:25:00.240 --> 00:25:03.760
She wrote in an unsentimental
essay called The King of the Birds.

00:25:03.760 --> 00:25:06.760
About the arrogance and
beauty of her peacocks

00:25:06.760 --> 00:25:08.570
and she wrote a poem, too.

00:25:08.570 --> 00:25:14.600
She sent a copy to her friend,
this is my first and last poem.

00:25:14.600 --> 00:25:20.420
I think poetry is a filthy habit
for a fiction writer to get in to.

00:25:20.420 --> 00:25:24.260
Let me read a little bit
from The Displaced Person,

00:25:24.260 --> 00:25:29.080
which I think is the best depiction
of the peculiar sort of farm life

00:25:29.080 --> 00:25:31.710
that Flannery knew so well.

00:25:31.710 --> 00:25:34.200
It was reflected in
a lot of her stories.

00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:37.310
So this is from The
Displaced Person.

00:25:37.310 --> 00:25:41.460
The peacock was following Mrs.
Shortley up the road to the hill

00:25:41.460 --> 00:25:43.580
where she meant to stand.

00:25:43.580 --> 00:25:48.340
Moving one behind the other, they
looked like a complete procession.

00:25:48.340 --> 00:25:51.830
Her arms were folded as
she mounted the prominence.

00:25:51.830 --> 00:25:55.910
She might have been the giant
wife of the countryside come

00:25:55.910 --> 00:26:00.360
out at some sign of danger
to see what the trouble was.

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:02.870
She stood on two tremendous legs

00:26:02.870 --> 00:26:06.350
with the grand self-confidence
of a mountain.

00:26:06.350 --> 00:26:10.570
And rose up narrowing bulges of
granite to two icy blue points

00:26:10.570 --> 00:26:15.570
of light that pierced
forward, surveying everything.

00:26:15.570 --> 00:26:17.460
She ignored the white afternoon sun

00:26:17.460 --> 00:26:20.780
that was creeping behind
a ragged wall of clouds

00:26:20.780 --> 00:26:23.650
as if it pretended
to be an intruder.

00:26:23.650 --> 00:26:26.670
And cast her gaze down
the red clay road

00:26:26.670 --> 00:26:29.560
that turned off from the highway.

00:26:29.560 --> 00:26:32.220 position:56%
The peacock stopped just behind her.

00:26:32.220 --> 00:26:34.890
His tail glittering
green, gold and blue

00:26:34.890 --> 00:26:37.040
in the sunlight lifted just enough

00:26:37.040 --> 00:26:39.360
so that it would not
touch the ground.

00:26:39.360 --> 00:26:42.660
It flowed out on either
side like a floating train.

00:26:42.660 --> 00:26:47.030
And his head on the long, blue,
reed like neck was drawn back

00:26:47.030 --> 00:26:50.390
as if his attention were
fixed in the distance

00:26:50.390 --> 00:26:53.710
on something no one else could see.

00:26:53.710 --> 00:26:56.180
Mrs. Shortley was watching
a black car turn

00:26:56.180 --> 00:26:58.450
through the gate from the highway.

00:26:58.450 --> 00:27:04.240
Over by the toolshed about 15 feet
away two negroes, Astor and Sulk,

00:27:04.240 --> 00:27:06.460
had stopped work to watch.

00:27:06.460 --> 00:27:08.120 position:56%
They were hidden by a mulberry tree,

00:27:08.120 --> 00:27:11.220
but Mrs. Shortley knew
they were there.

00:27:11.220 --> 00:27:15.620
Mrs. McIntyre was coming down the
steps of her house to meet the car.

00:27:15.620 --> 00:27:19.170
She had on her largest
smile but Mrs. Shortley,

00:27:19.170 --> 00:27:23.800
even from her distance, could
detect a nervous slide in it.

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:26.380
These people who were
coming were only hired help,

00:27:26.380 --> 00:27:30.080
like the Shortleys
themselves or like the negroes.

00:27:30.080 --> 00:27:33.710
Yet, here was the owner of
the place out to welcome them.

00:27:33.710 --> 00:27:37.330
Here she was, wearing her best
clothes and a string of beads

00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:41.080
and now bounding forward
with her mouth stretched.

00:27:41.080 --> 00:27:44.010
The car stopped at the
walk just as she did

00:27:44.010 --> 00:27:47.410
and the priest was
the first to get out.

00:27:47.410 --> 00:27:51.440
He was a long-legged black-suited
old man with a white hat on

00:27:51.440 --> 00:27:53.740 position:56%
and a collar that he wore backwards,

00:27:53.740 --> 00:27:56.970
which Mrs. Shortley knew
was what priests did

00:27:56.970 --> 00:27:59.940
who wanted to be known as priests.

00:27:59.940 --> 00:28:03.890
It was this priest who had arranged
for these people to come here.

00:28:03.890 --> 00:28:06.970
He opened the back door of the car

00:28:06.970 --> 00:28:09.490
and out jumped two
children, a boy and a girl.

00:28:09.490 --> 00:28:12.580
And then stepping more
slowly a woman

00:28:12.580 --> 00:28:15.640
in brown, shaped like a peanut.

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:17.060
Then the front door opened

00:28:17.060 --> 00:28:21.030
and out stepped the man,
the displaced person.

00:28:21.030 --> 00:28:22.790
He was short and a
little sway backed

00:28:22.790 --> 00:28:26.110
and wore gold-rimmed spectacles.

00:28:26.110 --> 00:28:29.540
Mrs. Shortley's vision
narrowed on him and then widened

00:28:29.540 --> 00:28:33.870
